        "content": "<p>We have <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=AlexandrovDiscrete#doc\">docs#AlexandrovDiscrete</a> but I can't seem to find the following:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>given any partial order on a type <code>X</code>, the upper sets form a (alexandrov) topology on <code>X</code>.</li>\n<li>the specialization partial order associated to the topology of (1) is the original partial order.</li>\n<li>Any alexandrov topological space arises in this way. </li>\n</ol>\n<p>Do we have such things in <code>mathlib</code>?</p>",
        "id": 496601584,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1738171906
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We do have <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Topology/AlexandrovDiscrete.html#isOpen_iff_forall_specializes\">isOpen_iff_forall_specializes</a> which essentially says that the specialization order determines the topology and vice-versa, but I still don't know how to talk about a poset as a topological space.</p>",
        "id": 496602443,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1738172155
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The \"upper\" topology in mathlib seems to be coarser than what you describe according to <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Topology/Order/LowerUpperTopology.html#Topology.IsUpper.isUpperSet_of_isOpen\">Topology.IsUpper.isUpperSet_of_isOpen</a></p>",
